Frisbee tossing and crab fighting…

You know you’re a disc golfer when you bring a frisbee with you everywhere! We also brought a handful of discs to play a few courses. Do you bring a catch disc or a few golf discs with you when you’re on vacation?

We had an experience of a lifetime yesterday watching the Sea Turtles come to shore. Definitely a day I’ll never forget.

Fast forward to this morning and I could see the light peeking through our window shades. Once again the sun was calling. I sat on our cute little porch and watched as the sun broke through the clouds. With the sound of waves crashing and roosters crowing, I felt at peace. This trip started out stressful but has turned into one @cmonty35876 and I will remember forever and we are only getting started..

Take me back to Estes Park 🤩 
Kona 🥵 you are STUNNING!

Can I just say that scan day is my favorite day. People aren't kidding when they say that it feels like Christmas. 

@rewindfilmlab thank you for the gorgeous scans.  These give me all the feels.

A day to remember! 

What started out as just a disc golf day, turned into a little excursion! After playing the insanely gorgeous Mauka DGC in Princeville we stopped by Hanalei Bay to check out some MASSIVE waves. On the way back to the resort we saw a pull off for the Kilauea lighthouse. It did not disappoint. Making memories out here with my bub! @cmonty35876

Unfortunately no dinosaurs but our helicopter ride felt like we were in a movie! Kauai is beautiful on the ground but man, seeing it from the sky was a check off the bucket list. Incredibly grateful for the life I live.
You walk up to hole 3, 416ft here at Mauka DGC with an insane view but OB water on the left. What disc are you grabbing to park this beautiful shot?

Since being on the island I’ve enjoyed seeing all the beautiful chickens and roosters. Last night while we were chowing down on some delicious Tikis Tacos, @cmonty35876 nightmare came true. The crazy little chicken jumped on our table and ate Colten’s Taco!!! 😡 

In Finland a crow tried to eat his hot dog. In San Francisco a seagull stole his $10 corn dog. Now a chicken stole his taco. I guess birds really like taking advantage of my husband! What the heck! 

Definitely a memory we will always look back on from our honeymoon🤣💝 Love you hun. I’ll protect you from the birds!
That was a close one… Loving the pop up on my Lucid-X Moonshine Trespass. Have you tried one out yet? They aren’t as overstable as I expected.. which I’m loving!!

Feeling fortunate to have spent our honeymoon in such a beautiful place. Today we head back to the frozen tundra that is Colorado and I don’t think we are truly prepared for it😅 Best three weeks of my life. 

What’s your favorite vacation of all time?

As we head into the New Year @cmonty35876 and I would like to give a huge thanks to @backstageorganics for supporting us these last two years as we part ways for the upcoming season. Field Work Sesh🤪

When I head to the field I love to focus on one particular part of my game. For this session I brought throwing putters and a few mids to focus on shorter approaches from 200ft and in. I like throwing every disc on different angles so I know what kind of flight I would get out of it if I needed to throw it a certain way on the course. Then from each approach I like to putt a handful of putters to not only get a cold putt from each disc but to also get my reps. 

How do you like to do fieldwork?

I’ve been playing disc golf on and off for all of my life. It’s hard to remember a time without it really. 

How long have you been playing?

The newest addition to my elemental series, The Leviathan Guard. When I joined @dynamicdiscs I knew I wanted to get some killer art added to the dyemax page. I work with some incredible artists that help bring my vision to life. It’s also crazy they can transfer any photo or illustration onto a disc for people to throw! Make sure to check out the Dyemax page to learn more and to see what molds they have available. Stay tuned for the final piece to my series…

Health update🍎

This past month has been so stressful dealing with the unknowns of my condition. I will say, there have been a few bright spots through this whole experience. I’ve started to “hack my health”. @hannahemcbeth_ recommend @keepyourplantson a few weeks ago and I’m proud to say I’ve joined her weekly group meetings and have been diving head first into nutrition and what my body truly needs both as an athlete and someone suffering with a thyroid condition. It’s been so enlightening listening to the stories of the other women in our group. I finally have people who I can relate to!! It’s an incredible feeling. I’ve always been somewhat of a health nut but having Lindsay there to guide me and have her knowledge to help back it up has been a relief to say the least. 

START TODAY! Listen to your body! Eat better! Live life to the fullest!!!🤍🤍🤍

Simple. Confident. Direct. 

These are three things I’ve been focusing on when it came to developing a putt I could use consistently on the road. You know me, I’ve tried all the styles of putting. I’ve taken all that experience and have found a putt I’m excited about! Feels good to be making the big ones with confidence. There are still some minor tweaks to adjust but they are small and I know will be effective during the season! 

What are three things you focus on when perfecting your putt?
See you at Discovering the World @dtworld_discs 10-11:30am tomorrow (Sat)! 🥏🥏
Why it’s important to incorporate your left arm when throwing backhand!
Perspective. It’s my motto for 2023. Family, friends, health, and all that I love in disc golf. Looking forward to all of it.

What it’s all about!

Yesterday when we were at our favorite park doing some fieldwork we noticed @garylewis6531 and @artc_photography searching for their new discs they just got off of Amazon. @cmonty35876 and I knowing that the bushes at Ralph are like black holes, decided to go over and help look. What started as a search for discs turned into some fun conversations about disc golf and life. I grabbed them some of my “Nice” discs and we got to throw a little bit before it got too dark. 

It’s moments like these that make us shake our heads and truly wonder how we got so lucky to call this our job. Couldn’t be more thankful for the life we live and the people we meet!

Sorry for the random emoji, didn’t want to spoil my 2023 tour series quite yet🫶🏻👀

Staying hydrated on the course while meeting fellow Escape throwers like Trent! He even had the @bushnell_disc Disc Jockey to jam out to on his cart😎🎶

I had the pleasure of giving a private lesson to Ryan yesterday! The first of 2023🤠 

I truly love when I get the opportunity to talk form with another disc golfer! I’m hoping I can try and do more clinics or lessons while on the road as it’s something I enjoy doing and helps grow our sport. I’m hoping some of the things we talked about during our lesson can help Ryan with his disc golf journey🥏

If you don’t have a local pro or can’t get a lesson, I always recommend videoing yourself. When I first started, my dad and I would go out to the field and record me throwing then head back home to compare it to some of the greats. We’d see what I was doing wrong then head back out to the field to try to correct it.

New Year, new bag! I’ve been rocking the Northern Lights Mission rig for the past year so I thought it was time to bust out the Topography version. 

I’m big into key chains as you can see… Do you customize your bag? If so, do you have a favorite trinket? I love my Hawaii pineapple key chain. He’s adorable and makes me smile every time I look at it😊

Sunset fieldwork with mi amor🥏

I wasn’t feeling the best, but getting outside and throwing some discs felt 👌🏼

Make sure to check out my interview on the Basket Case podcast! Gets intense and shows you a side of disc golf that not everyone gets to see. You can listen on most platforms but I listened to mine on Apple Podcasts.

What do you use disc golf for? For an escape, for exercise, to feed your competitive nature?

In my opinion it goes… 
Maverick if you want a super straight fairway driver.
Escape if you want a similar flight to the Mav but more distance. Then the Trespass for the same kind of S-Curve flights like the Maverick and Escape, but max distance😍

Surround yourself with the right people. 

I may have a small “close” friend group but that’s for a good reason. I’ve spent lots of time and effort on some people and either they were going nowhere with their lives or simply didn’t give that same kind of love back. These few are a different breed. Constantly looking for new ways to improve themselves, help those around them and make goals they can keep. Accountability is what I see in all of these people and they hold me to the same standards which I cannot thank them enough for. 

Don’t get me wrong, I also feel like I have a lot of friends and acquaintances through people I’ve met through disc golf, but these are my diehards. Love you guys🤍 

Tag the people you are thankful for🫶🏻

Please send all the good vibes, prayers and love my way today!

Today is a very important day for me. As I’ve mentioned in recent posts, I have been struggling with some health issues involving my thyroid. Today I get a biopsy on a node that is currently on my thyroid gland. This biopsy is going to tell us if the node cancerous or not. (I hate even saying that word). 

I’ve been stressed out of my mind. Seems like everyday for the past month I’ve been thinking about this day. My poor husband has been so great at dealing with my stress. So very thankful for him. 
I am excited to get some answers and I’m positive about the outcome and no matter what, I know I have a support system around me that has my back if I get the greatest news back. 

Love you guys. Cross your fingers and toes for me🤍

Sometimes when we go to our favorite park Ralph M Lewis, there isn’t quite enough space to unleash drives This time we went outside the fenced in area and threw from the walkways that wrap around the park. 

Do you ever make your own course?? 

Health update: I’m currently waiting on some results but wanted to say how overwhelmed I was with all of the love you all sent my way on Wednesday before my biopsy. So thankful for this community. The procedure was pretty miserable and I’ve been eating lots of smoothies & soup because of the swelling causing some discomfort when I swallow. I will say that I had my first normal meal last night which gave my anxiety some relief. Impatiently waiting for results but staying positive as always🤍🤍🤍

#ThankfulThursday

I’m hoping to making Thankful Thursday a weekly thing. Once a week I will reflect on things in my life on and off the course that I am thankful for. With the stress of getting ready for tour, sprinkled with the anxiety of my health issues I have to force myself to see the bright side. 

So this week I am thankful for disc golf and it’s community. When I’m at the course, nothing else matters. I’m focused on the flight of the disc, trajectory of the putt and being in the moment. 
The DG community is something else. One of the main reasons I got back into disc golf in high school at a more serious level was because of the community and the amazing people in it. I’ve received so much love these last few weeks and it means so much to me. 

Forever thankful.

All in all I was just happy to be out there. Having @steversnyder on the bag was an added bonus to the weekend! He kept the mood light, celebrated with me on the good shots and picked me up on the bad ones. Having @enysmiles10 walk the course with us and watch from afar was so great. She even helped get one of my discs back😍🫶🏻 The best. 
The highlight of the weekend was making some great putts under pressure. There were a few that I wish I had some mulligans for but it was nice to be hitting chains more consistently again. 😍

We are headed back to California so I can meet with some specialists and to get more answers on my thyroid. I will update when we head back out on the road soon!

Balance. 

Balance is such a key component to backhand form. Having your balance centered. Not falling backwards, not falling all the way forward.

The video in the next slide depicts it perfectly! This was a POWER shot. Fast run up, full reach back and a strong pull through. Notice at the end that my weight is centered and I’m not falling all over the place. 

Proud of how far my form has come. And it’s still evolving!

Back when we were just friends and she was showing me around LA for my first time. It’s crazy that 5 years later we are married and have a list a mile long of all the things we have done and seen since then. It was cool to go back and relive some of the memories we made just a handful of years ago. A lot has happened since then and I’m glad to have you by my side for all of it 💚 @kona_disc

Fun putting game!

Is putting practice boring to you? Spice it up! We spaced out 10 putters evenly all the way back to 50 feet. Start close to the basket and once you make it from the first station move back. The more chill version is to stay at the same station if you miss. If you want to make it more interesting, if you miss you have to go back to the previous station. Tons of fun competition with my bub and I got some good practice in. 

Do you play any putting games??

We will be missing Waco and will not be on the road for a little while. 

I may be having surgery to have my thyroid removed. Currently looking at a second opinion and have another biopsy lined up so we can have more information. It’s been a very frustrating process and the unknowns have been eating away at us. I’m thankful for my amazing husband being there for me through it all. My family has been amazing at supporting me and our sponsors have been wonderful in understanding that my health needs to come first. We are looking into maybe playing some events close by or maybe flying out to some depending on how long we are home and how things shake out. Thank you all for the love. Will keep you updated.

Head over to my YouTube channel to catch a fun unboxing of some sick @lorediscs! We had a blast making this for y’all! 

What other fun videos do you want to see from Hot KoCo?

The evenings have turned into painting opportunities! 

The oh so kind @a_isforautumn messaged me a few days ago asking how I was. I told her I was struggling with the fact that usually we would be on the road but instead we are in limbo waiting for some more results for at the moment. She mentioned I should try and keep busy and to do art or whatever I needed to to keep my mind off of things. Well, she opened a can of worms because now I’m obsessed with making minis when there’s any free time. I’ll be putting a protective spray on each one of these to keep them safe on the course. These minis will be available for purchase on our website discelf.com soon!

We met Atlas at our favorite practice spot yesterday. He was obsessed with watching the disc go in the basket and never once tried to pick one up or bite it. He would be a perfect disc golf dog! Let’s just say I almost stole Atlas…

Martha McLean has a challenging but incredibly fun finishing hole. Thanks @eric_mccabe 😉 So the question is… 305ft STRAIGHT uphill. Are you going for the basket through the double mando or laying up to the mouth, throwing an approach and taking the easy par?
I think this might be a fun segment we do on the channel more often! I always have a blast with my honey. Unfortunately for him my Fuzion Burst Evader did not fly 390ft. 😂🫶🏻

The new @latitude_64 Savior!

So many new molds coming out! Have you tried any? What plastics are you liking?

@cmonty35876 and I had a blast at the 7th Annual Ice Bowl at Prado Regional Park. This was a Charity event with all proceeds going to Chino Neighborhood House. We were stoked to be a part of it, donate some items to the raffle and run some some aces. Make sure you watch the whole video to see two ace runs! Shoutout to @cosmicfooldiscgolf for hosting the events and inviting @cmonty35876 and I out to play. We had a blast.

Itching to get back out there…

@cmonty35876 are looking to hit the road soon. Thinking that Music City will be our first event back. I plan to get my thyroid removed in the off-season. As of right now the node has shrunk. (What the heck?)
I’ll take it as great news though. Right now it’s not effecting my everyday life so I’m done waiting around. I’ve seen a few doctors. My Endo being one that I trust. I’ve had a rough experience with most of the appointments I’ve been to and tests that I have had done. I’m fed up. I’m not giving up. I have more knowledge than I ever had before about my condition. I just don’t think it should hold up my life anymore and I won’t die tomorrow. I’ll continue to monitor everyday and get blood work done while we are on the road as well. 

I also have a nutritionist that teaches me something new every week. I am taking the steps to live a healthy life. I’m glad I got some answers and that I didn’t just live without knowing. 

I appreciate everyone that reached out and sent all the good vibes and prayers. These past few years have been very trying but this sport and it’s community have been wonderful. Shoutout to my loyal peeps too. You know who you are😉❤️

Tag the person you trust the most when you need help with a part of your game!

Two of my best drives from the Beaver State Fling presented by Innova discs. First slide is with my super beat Royal Grace and the second slide is with my Orbit Getaway🤩

Shoutout to @bradleydiscgolf and @throw_like_lucky for the good vibes on final day and for getting these videos! 

Moral of the story is that the mind is a powerful thing. On both of these drives I was aggressive and didn’t think twice. When I walked up to what felt like a short putt I was instantly met with fear and the feeling of wanting the putt to go in so badly that I wasn’t truly in the moment. I ended up missing the birdie putt and going OB turning my beautiful birdie into a bogey. It was depressing and I was deflated after this hole/ round. 

After some reflection I know my results are not a representation of who I am. Parts of my game are so money while others need a lot of work both mentally and physically but we are out here doing it.

The backhand drive is such an interesting throw. 

You’re turning your body away from the basket and relying on pure trust when pulling through. Hoping to hit the line you intended to when lining up the shot. When I step on the tee not a lot is going through my mind. What I focus on most is before the actual shot. I walk to the end of the tee where I want to plant. Sometimes I’ll check the footing, depends on conditions. I then aim at something so incredibly small in the distance. I started doing this after reading the book, “Golf is not a game of perfect”. 

What’s going through your mind when you’re on the tee??

ACE!!!! 

After a five year dry spell, I finally hit an ace! At the beginning of the round @cmonty35876 said, “I have a feeling you’re going to ace this round.” Sure enough, we got to hole 18 270ft at Meier Lake with my Fuzion Burst Evidence in hand. I threw it on a super flat angle and it barely fade into the basket. Oh how it feels so good to hit an ace!

Check out some shots from Meier Lake DGC!

This track has been such a blast to play. From the short pad you can really score on most of the holes but from the long tees to the long pins, it’s definitely more challenging and you need to be mindful of the angles you release your discs on or they can end up in some rough spots!

Discs I’m leaning on:
🩵2023 Orbit Escape🩵 This years Escape is a tad more overstable than the 2022 version. Which means I can put it on a tad of an anny and it’ll pan out. So good. 
🩵Fuzion Burst Evidence🩵 For those straight tunnel shots, I know I can hit the Evidence pretty hard and it’ll just go dead straight. I mean I already aced with it on this course so it’s definitely one I’ll be throwing a lot. 
🩵Fuzion Orbit Getaway🩵 When I need something to get left. This is the disc I’m grabbing. It’s not OVERLY overstable but it definitely has some stability when I need to it. 
🩵 @zmelton38631 Fuzion-X Orbit Maverick🩵 (not in the video slide). This thing is FLIPPY! Which makes it such a go-to in the woods. I don’t have throw it massively hard to get that nice hyzer flip to flat.

It’s crazy how one simple change can improve your game. This week, it was figuring out my early release. I don’t usually have to worry about my backhand form but it got so annoyingly bad that I knew something was up. Hope this helps anyone else struggling with this in their form!

Our guide Connor was 22 years old and was experienced in every aspect of our tour. Not once did I feel unsafe! I’m proud of myself for being able to hike through some gnarly terrain like the Moraine and narrow ice walls with water rushing through it. I’m usually someone who doesn’t do things like this but I’m incredibly happy that I did. Especially with my husband. What an experience.

The heel can either come down, allowing me to “Slip” them on or I can also have the heel up so I can “Speed” to wherever I need to go. I like to call it 4-wheel mode😂 
They’re also my go-to after a long round in hot and nasty trail shoes. They have an ISO-Chill interior making them super comfortable to slip into after a long day. I bet you’re also wondering why I got a white pair? I thought I was crazy picking white as well, but these babies are machine washable! You best believe I’ll be throwing them in the washer after our Alaska trip!

I opt for flex forehands when the corner is too tight for a couple reasons:
-I always tend to hit early if I try to throw the backhand on a tight hyzer-flip kind of shot. 
-I don’t have to look away from the tight corner and the small aiming point I’m trying to hit.
-I can focus on the angle better and know if I just throw something decently overstable like my Chameleon Justice, that it’ll pan out at the basket.

I’ve been REALLY struggling with my putt lately. I know..shocker.. not really. I feel like I’ve got to a point where I’m stepping up to a putt and am so hyper focused on what my body feels/looks like that after the disc has left my hand I couldn’t tell you where I was aiming. It’s been upsetting to say the least as this is my job and also my biggest passion. I put a lot of time into practice putting but I never see it translate over when it counts. 
So here’s my goal for today during my practice round.. Trust the putt and focus on a chain. Walk up to every putt with confidence that I may not feel but using the “fake it until you make it” mentality until I do feel that confidence. 
I love this game so much man. You have no idea how bad I want it. Maybe too bad sometimes. As of right now though, I’m just asking for consistency when it comes to hitting chains. 

I don’t know why I’ve struggled for what feels like forever. I’d say ever since high school when I started taking disc golf more seriously that I’ve had a hard time with my short game. My anxiety definitely plays tricks with my head but I’m trying and I’m out here. So until I’m not out here, catch me grinding.

I’m internally screaming because I just talked about how I want to grind it out and work hard to figure out my game. Now I can’t even try. 
This year has been tough. Injuries, pain and not a lot of results. I’m hoping this will give me time to heal but also time to strengthen the mental side of things.

Rangefinder tip: Scan Mode 

A lot of people don’t know about Scan Mode and it can make your rangefinder experience a lot easier. Click the button on your @bushnell_disc Edge Rangefinder once to turn on. Thanks to all of you who send DMs and comments on tips. I figured why not share them with all of you. So, here’s my first in a series of PRO TIPS… 

One Marker Disc.

Back in 2018, at the Music City Open, I walked up to a drive that I bombed down the fairway, marked it, and put the disc off the the side. I walked back to my bag, grabbed a disc, thought about the shot and prepared to throw. There may have been a distraction before I was clear to go. Then, boom! I sent the upshot at the basket. In the heat of competition and with the tall grass of the fairway I didn’t notice I setup my shot from the wrong lie! 😩 Once I threw the shot and looked down to get my mini, I realized it immediately—“Eeek! That’s not my mini, it’s the disc I set aside!”. I explained the misplay to my card and threw again from my correct lie. I had to take an extra stroke for my mistake but learned a lesson that day and now whenever I mark my lie, I put the disc back in the bag!

Mail call!

Today I got a package from Kona that she sent me as she heads back on tour just in time for Worlds!  There was a nice note for me (the card has veggies that say “Totally rooting for you!”) as well as a couple discs and stickers inside.  I think I’m excited to try the sparkly Escape out the most!

Dad also had me open a box that came in the mail last week… he got our family the latest Birdie game with a new Fox Run expansion course (which is one of the courses Worlds is going to play at next weekend). Hopefully we can play it soon for a family game night!

Feels good to be out on the road again! Right after I landed we made a little pit stop at Niagara Falls😍 If you’ve never been at night, I highly recommend it. 

We stopped at a few courses yesterday to stretch the legs and so I could get back to throwing. Thankfully the courses we stopped at had shorter holes so I got to slowly start chucking again. The form feels great! If anything my release is a little off here and there but I’m not too worried about it. The putt feels pretty disgusting at the moment. I have moments where it feels great, the pop is how I want it, the release is smooth and then there are other moments that I wonder what the heck happened😂 The joys of not playing for a hot minute. I’m looking to do practice putting but in small increments for each session.

My first practice round at Brewster Ridge was exactly how I expected it to be. Frustrating but so much fun. This course is in my top 3 favorites of all time so to come back and get a solo round in on this course was a treat. Slowly getting the drive and putt back!

Touchy Backhand Anhyzers 
This shot used to be one that I would dread throwing. I’d always opt for the forehand if I could. I’m now forcing myself to throw them during practice rounds where I would throw a forehand so I can get more confident with the release and power in case this shot arises in the event. I keep telling myself “be smooth with it!” The problem I have most is getting my head stuck, meaning I don’t turn with the shot and this usually leads to an early release for me. So making sure everything is rotating together is huge for me! Also keeping the disc on the angle I want to throw it on is always a good pro tip! 
🥏 The Supreme Judge and Moonshine EMac Judge have been staples for this shot.

I got some Worlds Practice in at Fox Run with some of my faves! @dani.kleidon33 and @madddie13 are two people I can be unapologetically myself with. There aren’t a lot of people I feel like I do do that with so I always cherish the rounds I get in with y’all! Everything is feeling good, plus my drive is feeling very simple and effortless. I started my day at my Endocronologist. We did an ultrasound and she had found that my nodules had shrunk. Meaning the work @dddwellness and I have been doing has definitely been helping. I left feeling good but also a little frustrated that we weren’t able to do a biopsy to see if it was truly cancer. 
Later in the day I had a consult scheduled. Without realizing it, the location was 48 min away. In my mind I thought it was only a 10 minute drive so mom and I hopped in the car and although we got there late, they still took me🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻 I’m so glad they did because when my ENT took a look she immediately saw some suspicious areas. Within 5 minutes we were in another room preparing for a biopsy. 
If you’ve been following my journey you know the last experience I had with a biopsy was absolutely traumatizing. This was such a night and day difference compared to the first one. They were kind, they made sure I didn’t feel much pain and were able to take 10 samples total from two different nodes. We are hoping out of all of those 10 samples we are able to get some solid answers. If not we do a procedure where they actually go in and remove a part of the node and test it. 

I’m currently at my gate at the airport waiting to fly to Burlington, NC for the USWDGC. On a scale from 1-10 I’m at a 5 for pain which is amazing compared to the first experience. I might be a little sore but I’m excited to compete and happy we were able to get in to the ENT. 

Send some good vibes my way and I’ll keep y’all updated🫶🏻🫶🏻🫶🏻

Well, the end of the season has drastically changed since I last informed y’all. Right before I was about to walk into massage envy to get a massage my ENT called me to let me know my results came back at Thyroid Cancer. I feel like I’ve known this for some time now but to have a definite answer brought both relief and fear. Things are moving fast and I have a pre-op appt on Monday and surgery estimated on Friday the 6th. I’m happy to get things moving and to be cancer free soon.

Post-op update! Mom and hubby were amazing at taking good care of me after surgery. I also have to give a huge shoutout to the nurses and doctors who have been every step of the way. Everyone has been so kind and helpful, I’m so grateful. 
I was feeling pretty good right after the surgery. Other than some chest pain and it being difficult to swallow, I was doing great. I will have that JP drain in my neck at least until Tuesday to help drain any extra fluid. It looks so gnarly and thankfully it’s not putting as much out as time goes by so that’s good. 
Fast forward to the afternoon when they moved me into my private room, Colten was feeding me some soup when all of a sudden I didn’t feel so hot and threw up. They said this is normal as a reaction from the anesthesia. Thankfully it only happened once and I was feeling much better after the fact. Poor Bub literally left the hospital just to get that soup and I didn’t even get to enjoy it☹️
Bubba ended up driving back to the house around 8pm to rest up while mama bear stayed the night with me in the hospital. I’m so thankful she was here with me. As you can tell from the last photo, it was a rough night. It seemed like I was waking up every other hour to either pee, get more pain meds or reposition. The numbness is definitely wearing off around the incision site and the area where they removed the extra nodes near my sternum is in a decent amount of pain but I’m doing okay. 
I will say, I wish I could take this bed home😂 The reclining ability is amazing and will be missed when I have to go back to my own bed😂 
Thank you all for the love and messages. It’s been a lot to deal with but having so many people support me through this has been amazing. Can’t imagine doing this alone. I hope I can be a light to those who may need a surgery similar to mine and I can help answer any questions some may have. Overall, my experience has been a good one. Much love.

Update: I haven’t been on my phone too much. Maybe when I needed a distraction from the pain or nausea but we made it home Saturday evening. It was a rough ride back as I was nauseous driving in the car. Thankfully Kyle did a good job getting us back safe and sound. It was nice to finally get some uninterrupted sleep. It felt like the nurses and doctors were waking me up every other hour to check on me. 
Yesterday I was doing really well eating food and moving around until I took some pain meds that made me extremely nauseous. I then “rid” myself of most everything I ate. Joy. Since then I haven’t taken the heavy medicine and have been relying on Tylenol. I’d rather deal with some pain then with the way the other made me feel. 
The days have been full of naps, short walks in the hallway and just trying to deal with the discomfort. I’ve been trying so hard to be strong and tell myself the pain is temporary but I have broken down a couple of times. I feel very stiff and need help doing a lot of things, which I hate asking for help. I’m a very self-reliant person so it’s been hard asking for things. I feel like I apologize a lot but my fam keep reminding me that they are here for me and happy to do whatever I need. Very thankful for them. 
Brother Ky headed back to Georgia late last night. It was nice having him home for awhile🫶🏻 Always love when the whole fam is together. 
My pup Ares has been making visits everyday to my room to say hi and give me kisses. He never comes upstairs so it’s been really sweet. They always say animals can sense when something is up🫶🏻 
Tomorrow I get my JP drain removed. I’m not looking forward to what that is going to feel like but it’ll be nice to get this tube out of me. Much love to everyone who has been so kind through all this. I say thank you every time I post but it’s because I mean it. Much love.

He mentioned some people lie about the amount they are putting out just so they can get the drain out and that’s why they didn’t tell me the amount I needed to be putting out before getting it removed🥲 I’m bummed but know it’s best to keep it in so it doesn’t just pool in my neck. Recovery update❤️‍🩹

My battle scar is healing quite nicely. The glue has finally come off, minus a few bits, but I am pleasantly surprised in how it looks after only 2 weeks. I’m still quite sore and notice when it’s time to take more Tylenol when it becomes hard to swallow. I’m trying to exercise my neck more and moving my shoulder is getting easier everyday. Physical therapy starts next week. I still find myself quite tired after doing normal everyday activities but that will get better in time. 

A lot of people have messaged me asking why I have such a large scar. Some ask because they have friends or family who need to get their thyroid removed or have had them removed and it looked nothing like mine. In my case I had cancerous nodes on the right side of my neck and the only way to remove them was to cut all the way up to the base of my ear. This photo is the first time I’ve truly been able to see the full thing in all its glory. Now that the glue has come off I feel so much better about it. The glue made it look all purple and scary but now that I can see it, it just looks like a line. In due time it’ll just look like a crease in my neck and to those who notice and ask, I’ll be able to tell them about my battle and how I found a doctor who gave a hoot and took care of me.

Recovery Update🩹
For some reason I didn’t notice that I went live on my other account with my recent update. Silly goose. After several phone calls and leaving messages at my Endocrinologists office, I had my dad drive me so I could try to speak to someone face to face. I was finally able to speak to the office manager who convinced me to speak to my Endo about the next steps🙄 Although I had no intention on seeing her, I knew she would at least give me the information I’ve been needing to move forward. After going over my pathology report, we talked about radioactive iodine. Next Monday I’ll stop taking my thyroid medication to starve my body of TSH. This will make it easier for the Radioactive Iodine to attack any thyroid cells left and hopefully leave me cancer free when all is said and done. A week after stopping that I will go in and take the Radioactive Iodine pill in their office. I’ll have 4 days of isolation where I can’t be around anyone and will have to be careful with what I touch and eat. Then I’ll have a scan done to see if it worked🥳 
My appetite has been great, my calcium and magnesium have been good and I’m looking forward to getting this last bit over with. I’ve been doing my PR exercises everyday and although massaging around my scar is incredible weird, my movement is improving. Happy as a clam 🫶🏻

To celebrate five weeks postop I decided to get up and do my hair and make up. Things I don’t do very often. Lately, I haven’t felt the prettiest. Having a giant scar on my neck has made that hard lately. I will say, having my amazing husband @cmonty35876 tell me every single day that I am beautiful and perfect the way I am has definitely helped.
 I never really think, “why is this happening to me?” I’ve never been that kind of person. Although the thoughts that have run through my mind are more like, “is this really happening?” “is this real life?” Because at times it kind of feels like a dream. Throughout this whole process I feel like I’ve been very positive and always looking for answers to any questions I have about what’s next. These last five weeks have really taught me a lot. I feel like I’m more appreciative of the small things. For example, spending more quality time with my family has been a blessing these past five weeks. I’ve been out on the road the past five years and although during the off-season I get to see them, I haven’t had the quality time that I have these past few weeks. I feel more brave and feel like I’m living more by the “life is too short” mantra. This past week Colten and I attended one of our really good friends wedding. Usually I would just sit at our table and chill. Although I was exhausted and stiff I made a point to go out and dance on that dance floor. I also feel like my confidence in doing things that scare me grows more and more every day. 
It’s been an eye-opening experience, and I can see the finish line in sight. Just a few more weeks, and this can hopefully all just be a memory, and also another page in my life journey.

This time last year I was surrounded by the ones I love. Thanksgiving is a favorite holiday of mine as it’s all about coming together and eating good food. I hope to those celebrating today, you will hug your fam & friends a little harder for me. Yesterday I was given my Radioactive Iodine Treatment. I’m thankful my TSH was high enough and my iodine was low enough to go through with the procedure. The diet is the worst part. I don’t know how I would’ve felt having to wait another week so that was a blessing. I was taken to the basement of the hospital where they keep everything and the nurse brought in the “lead pig” (I believe that’s what it is called) with two of the radioactive iodine pills. I received a dose of 150 millicuries, 200 being the most they usually can give you. I was given such a high dose because my cancer had spread to more areas than my thyroid, including a small part of my lymphatic system. The nurse used a device to detect the radiation in my system (that was freaky) and I immediately had to stay at least 3 feet away from my mom who drove me to the hospital. Makes you feel a bit like a lab rat. I was feeling fine last night. I’d wake up every other hour to drink some water or suck on a lemon drop as my mouth has become dry and I worry about my salivary glands. It wasn’t until 3am this morning when I started to feel the pain and swelling in my neck meaning the RAI had finally settled in. I have steroids if it becomes too uncomfortable but for now it’s just a little painful and sore. Pain is temporary and this needed to happen. One day at a time. Shoutout to my mom @denise_panis for being so amazing and driving me to appointments, making me food whenever I ask and simply being there for me through it all. This hasn’t been easy but I thankful I have her and my dad here to help out🫶🏻

Tell them you love them.

Today I got a PET CT scan. 

If you’re claustrophobic this type of scan is quite stressful. Thankfully I don’t have a hard time in small spaces but I will say I struggled at the start of the 25 minute skull to thigh scan and was worried I was going to twitch or move. The unfortunate part of this scan is laying down with your arms above your head the whole time. To distract my mind I played a round of disc golf at one of my favorite courses in my head, The bEast in Waco🫶🏻 Of course all of the shots were perfect😂I envisioned what @dynamicdiscs Disc I would throw on each tee, where it would land and what my upshot would look like. I even envisioned banging the putt on every tricky green on the course. It made the time pass and distracted me from my arms that were slowly falling asleep. After the 25 minute scan from skull to thigh, they allowed me to drop my arms (thank gosh) and did a 15 minute head and chest CT scan and by the end of it I was tapping out on hole 18. Just goes to show how much I’m missing disc golf lately and how much I truly love this sport and all it’s done for me! This video was from 2022 when I played Waco last. Hope to be back soon🫶🏻

Scar care with KMonty🫶🏻 

These are three habits I’ve got in the routine of doing everyday. Vitamin E oil and Moderna have been two creams that have made the healing process go smoothly. 
Cross-friction massage was a struggle for me at the start of my recovery process. I was scared to touch it, didn’t know how hard to massage and I was overall nervous to go near my scar. It took me going to my PT to show me that I’m not a porcelain doll and that our bodies are truly incredible. Now everyday it’s just part of my check list! 
I’ve talked about this one a lot, but it is important for the first year to keep my scar out of the sun. Sunscreen is in my scar cream, but I’ve started wearing some really cute silk scarves to help protect it from the sun. 

Hope y’all enjoyed some insight into my recovery process. I’ll be sharing more soon!

I worked out at the gym for the first time in awhile. A lot of my exercises I can do at home with resistance bands and body weight but I wanted to go to the gym for a little motivation. As you can see in this photo the trap on my right side is non-existent compared to my left. This is due to lack of movement and a result of my surgery leaving my shoulder very weak afterwards. I didn’t think it would be to this extent but it’s where we are at. My shoulder is feeling better and better everyday. The more mobility I do, the more I feel the itch to play again. Shoutout to @discgolfstrong for helping me through my recovery process. I’ll be filming more of workouts and what I’m doing to get back to 100% soon so stay tuned.
